plotText.plainText: Three World War II veterans, two of them traumatized or disabled, return home to the American midwest to discover that they and their families have been irreparably changed.

caption.plainText: The Exorcist (1973)

plotText.plainText: When a 12-year-old girl is possessed by a mysterious entity, her mother seeks the help of two priests to save her.

caption.plainText: Bill Murray and Andie MacDowell in Groundhog Day (1993)

plotText.plainText: A self-centered Pittsburgh weatherman finds himself inexplicably trapped in a small town as he lives the same day over and over again.

caption.plainText: Samuel L. Jackson, Holly Hunter, Jason Lee, Craig T. Nelson, Brad Bird, Sarah Vowell, and Spencer Fox in The Incredibles (2004)

plotText.plainText: A family of undercover superheroes, while trying to live the quiet suburban life, are forced into action to save the world.

caption.plainText: La haine (1995)

plotText.plainText: 24 hours in the lives of three young men in the French suburbs the day after a violent riot.

caption.plainText: Jack Benny and Carole Lombard in To Be or Not to Be (1942)

originalTitleText.text: To Be or Not to Be

plotText.plainText: During the Nazi occupation of Poland, an acting troupe becomes embroiled in a Polish soldier's efforts to track down a German spy.

caption.plainText: Johnny Depp, Geoffrey Rush, Orlando Bloom, and Keira Knightley in Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl (2003)

titleText.text: Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl

originalTitleText.text: Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl

plotText.plainText: Blacksmith Will Turner teams up with eccentric pirate "Captain" Jack Sparrow to save his love, the governor's daughter, from Jack's former pirate allies, who are now undead.

caption.plainText: Richard Gere and Joan Allen in Hachi: A Dog's Tale (2009)

plotText.plainText: A college professor bonds with an abandoned dog he takes into his home.

caption.plainText: Fusia El Kader and Jean Martin in La battaglia di Algeri (1966)

plotText.plainText: In the 1950s, fear and violence escalate as the people of Algiers fight for independence from the French government.

caption.plainText: Henry Fonda, John Carradine, Jane Darwell, Dorris Bowdon, Frank Darien, and Russell Simpson in The Grapes of Wrath (1940)

plotText.plainText: An Oklahoma family driven off their farm by the poverty and hopelessness of the Dust Bowl joins the westward migration to California, suffering the misfortunes of the homeless in the Great Depression.

caption.plainText: Subir Banerjee in Pather Panchali (1955)

plotText.plainText: Impoverished priest Harihar Ray, dreaming of a better life for himself and his family, leaves his rural Bengal village in search of work.

caption.plainText: Suriya in Jai Bhim (2021)

plotText.plainText: When a tribal man is arrested for a case of alleged theft, his wife turns to a human-rights lawyer to help bring justice.

caption.plainText: Amores perros (2000)

plotText.plainText: A horrific car accident connects three stories, each involving characters dealing with loss, regret, and life's harsh realities, all in the name of love.

caption.plainText: Hümeyra, Fikret Kuskan, Çetin Tekindor, Günal Sen, Özge Özberk, and Ege Tanman in Babam ve Oglum (2005)

plotText.plainText: The family of a left-wing journalist is torn apart after the military coup of Turkey in 1980.

caption.plainText: Kim Min-hee, Ha Jung-woo, Cho Jin-woong, and Kim Tae-ri in Ah-ga-ssi (2016)

plotText.plainText: A woman is hired as a handmaiden to a Japanese heiress, but secretly she is involved in a plot to defraud her.

caption.plainText: Rebecca (1940)

plotText.plainText: A self-conscious woman juggles adjusting to her new role as an aristocrat's wife and avoiding being intimidated by his first wife's spectral presence.

caption.plainText: Paul Newman in Cool Hand Luke (1967)

plotText.plainText: A laid back Southern man is sentenced to two years in a rural prison, but refuses to conform.

caption.plainText: Julie Andrews, Christopher Plummer, Charmian Carr, Angela Cartwright, Duane Chase, Nicholas Hammond, Kym Karath, Heather Menzies-Urich, and Debbie Turner in The Sound of Music (1965)

plotText.plainText: A young novitiate is sent by her convent in 1930s Austria to become a governess to the seven children of a widowed naval officer.

caption.plainText: François Truffaut and Jean-Pierre Léaud in Les quatre cents coups (1959)

plotText.plainText: A young boy, left without attention, delves into a life of petty crime.

caption.plainText: Clark Gable and Claudette Colbert in It Happened One Night (1934)

plotText.plainText: A renegade reporter trailing a young runaway heiress for a big story joins her on a bus heading from Florida to New York, and they end up stuck with each other when the bus leaves them behind at one of the stops.

caption.plainText: Bibi Andersson and Liv Ullmann in Persona (1966)

plotText.plainText: A nurse is put in charge of a mute actress and finds that their personae are melding together.

caption.plainText: Life of Brian (1979)

plotText.plainText: Born on the original Christmas in the stable next door to Jesus Christ, Brian of Nazareth spends his life being mistaken for a messiah.

caption.plainText: The Iron Giant (1999)

plotText.plainText: A young boy befriends a giant robot from outer space that a paranoid government agent wants to destroy.

caption.plainText: Viola Davis, Bryce Dallas Howard, Octavia Spencer, and Emma Stone in The Help (2011)

plotText.plainText: An aspiring author during the civil rights movement of the 1960s decides to write a book detailing the African American maids' point of view on the white families for which they work, and the hardships they go through on a daily basis.

caption.plainText: Robin Williams, Jonathan Freeman, Gilbert Gottfried, Linda Larkin, Scott Weinger, and Frank Welker in Aladdin (1992)

plotText.plainText: A kindhearted street urchin and a power-hungry Grand Vizier vie for a magic lamp that has the power to make their deepest wishes come true.

caption.plainText: Kevin Costner in Dances with Wolves (1990)

plotText.plainText: Lieutenant John Dunbar, assigned to a remote western Civil War outpost, befriends wolves and Native Americans, making him an intolerable aberration in the military.
